	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nhgXh5zG4f0yY2nv0",
			"markdown": "Techs are the engineers, mechanics, hackers, inventors, and systems specialists who keep advanced societies functioning. Whether you are a grease-stained vehicle mechanic on a frontier colony, a cyberneticist modifying human bodies in a neon-lit megacity, a starship engineer keeping ancient machinery alive through sheer stubbornness, or a brilliant inventor building prototypes nobody else fully understands, you solve problems by understanding how things work. In cyberpunk settings, Techs may be corporate security specialists, black-market cyberware surgeons, underground hackers, or drone operators. In space opera and military campaigns, they are often ship engineers, armorers, combat engineers, maintenance crews, or technical officers responsible for keeping equipment operational under impossible conditions. Whatever form they take, Techs are the people everyone depends on when vital systems fail, equipment breaks down, or advanced technology becomes the difference between success and disaster.\n\nYour primary role is mastery of technology and infrastructure. A Tech is far more than someone who repairs broken equipment: you understand the systems that power civilization itself. Many Techs specialize in engineering, electronics, mechanics, demolitions, programming, cybersecurity, robotics, or industrial operations, developing expertise in skills such as Engineer, Mechanic, Electronics Repair, Computer Programming, Computer Hacking, Machinist, Explosives, or Armory. Even away from the workshop or terminal, you remain invaluable by bypassing security systems, modifying equipment, maintaining vehicles and weapons, improvising repairs in hostile environments, analyzing technical problems, or building tools the rest of the group cannot replace. Whether you are a disciplined corporate technician, a military engineer, a scavenger surviving on jury-rigged machinery, or a visionary inventor pushing technology beyond safe limits, the group depends on you whenever machines fail, systems break down, or advanced technology becomes the key to survival.\n\nThe *Cybertech* specializes in digital systems, networks, cybernetics, and electronic intrusion. You might be a corporate hacker, cybersecurity expert, drone operator, AI programmer, surveillance specialist, or underground cyberware technician. In cyberpunk settings, you are often the party’s connection to the digital world; in military or space campaigns, you may serve as an electronic warfare operator, signals intelligence specialist, or systems analyst. Your skills likely focus on Computer Hacking, Computer Programming, Electronics Operation, AI systems, surveillance technology, and security bypasses. Your technical obsession and isolation from ordinary social life may lead to disadvantages such as Obsession, Loner, Workaholic, or Low Empathy.\n\nThe *Field Mechanic* keeps vehicles, machinery, infrastructure, and battlefield equipment operational under brutal conditions with limited tools, improvised parts, and sheer determination. Frontier colony engineers, starship mechanics, industrial workers, salvage operators, convoy repair crews, and combat engineers all fall into this archetype. You may repair damaged vehicles under fire, bypass security systems, disarm explosives, restore failing reactors, or improvise solutions using whatever materials happen to be available. Your skills often focus on Mechanic, Machinist, Electrician, Engineer, Explosives, Hazardous Materials, Scrounging, and practical repair work. Years of dangerous labor and constant pressure frequently produce disadvantages such as Miserliness, Alcoholism, Overconfidence, Stubbornness, or Workaholic.\n\nThe *Inventor* develops new technologies, prototypes, modifications, and experimental systems that push beyond conventional engineering. Some Inventors are respected research scientists or corporate designers working at the cutting edge of civilization; others are eccentric garage tinkerers, rogue roboticists, or brilliant mechanics who constantly modify and improve existing technology. You thrive on experimentation, innovation, and solving problems nobody else can solve. Your skills commonly emphasize Engineer, Mathematics, Electronics, invention, and prototype development. Cinematic Inventors can possess the Gadgeteer trait, allowing them to produce astonishing devices and rapid breakthroughs, though this trait may not be appropriate for all campaigns and should be discussed with the GM. Inventors are often driven, eccentric, or consumed by their work, leading to disadvantages such as Obsession, Curious, Absent-Mindedness, Clueless, or Workaholic.\n\nThe *Security Tech* specializes in surveillance systems, technical security, controlled access, forensic analysis, and defensive infrastructure. Corporate troubleshooters, lock and sensor experts, covert entry specialists, technical investigators, and counterintrusion professionals all fit this archetype. You understand how secure systems are built — and how they fail. In espionage or cyberpunk campaigns, you may serve as the team’s infiltration expert; in military or frontier settings, you may protect sensitive facilities, monitor sensor networks, or investigate sabotage and system failures. Your skills often center on Electronics Operation, Computer Operation, Armory, sensors, access systems, and technical investigation. Constant secrecy, paranoia, and professional caution commonly result in disadvantages such as Secret, Loner, Honesty, Code of Honor (Professional), or Overconfidence."
		}
	]
}
